author: @martinmartin6300
text: Hey I'm very eager to know whether your inner training loop ("for example in batch") is actually parallelizrd on your GPU or how to achieve this. Otherwise, you probably waste some resources as your GPU has to hold while you switch in your CPU to the next example in batch as it is done on CPU I suppose? Especially when the GPU has more computing units than are needed for calculation of a layer you could do multiple layers in parallel on GPU which means that you actually need to throw multiple examples of a batch at the same time on your GPU.

text: Once again, great tutorial!  I was trying to figure out the GPU myself but I was missing the net.to(device) method.  Once done, it was golden!  The improvement was almost 50x my laptop speed which was awesome, keep up the great work, you have a gifted mind for this stuff. You may already have this planned for a future episode, but saving the trained model worked easily as well:   # Save trained model parameters torch.save(net.state_dict(), "./Models/net_7.pt")    # Load saved model parameters  if torch.cuda.is_available():     net.load_state_dict(torch.load("./Models/net_7.pt", map_location=torch.device('cuda:0')))  else:     net.load_state_dict(torch.load("./Models/net_7.pt", map_location=torch.device('cpu')))
